Project: Investigating No Show Appointments in Brazil¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

PURPOSE/DESCR: Approximately 30% of appointments in a certain dataset from Brazil are no-shows to their appoinments.

Over the course of this notebook, we will explore and observe trends among the different possible factors behind this. We will also try to develop an idea of what factors have a high correlation and high chance of being linked to whether or not one will go to their appointment. Finally, we will end by discussing the results of what we find as well as possible subjects of study in the future to get a better idea of what can eventually help us predict whether someone does or doesn't go to their appointment.

Data Cleaning¶

A really neat thing is that there are no null values, which is awesome for a dataframe!

However, the No-Show column is a little confusing in what it means, so we're gonna create a new column called 'Showed' with 1 being they were present for their appointment and 0 being a No-Show

Of course it's important to remember that Yes means they missed and No means they were present in the 'No-Show' column, so we'll have Yes map to 0 and No map to 1

After that we can drop the 'No-Show' column and look at our new data

In [6]:
#Let's make an extra col for No-show with Showed and values of 1 for Yes and 0 for No to make it easier
# to work with

# WRONG REMEMBER NO MEANS THEY SHOWED AND YES MEANS THEY DIDN"T SHOW
# "about the encoding of the last column: it says ‘No’ if the patient 
# showed up to their appointment, and ‘Yes’ if they did not show up."

#Then we can drop the No-show col since Showed answers that for us

df['Showed'] = df['No-show'].map(dict(Yes=0, No=1))
df.drop(['No-show'], axis=1, inplace=True)

numericCols = ['Scholarship', 'Hipertension', 'Diabetes', 'Alcoholism', 'SMS_received']
showedWithColMeans = []
showedWithoutColMeans = []
diffBetweenShowAndNoShowMeans = []
for col in numericCols:
    #showedColMeans.append(dfShowed[col].mean())
    colDf = df[df[col] == 1]
    print(col + ' means: ')
    print('percentage of those who showed with ' + col + ':')
    print(colDf.Showed.mean())
    showedWithColMeans.append(colDf.Showed.mean())
    colDf2 = df[df[col] == 0]
    print('percentage of those who showed without ' + col +':')
    print(colDf2.Showed.mean())
    showedWithoutColMeans.append(colDf2.Showed.mean())
    
    print('people with ' + col + ' were: ')
    
    #print(str(colDf.Showed.mean() - colDf2.Showed.mean()))
    print(str(colDf.Showed.mean() - colDf2.Showed.mean()) + ' percent more likely to show than those without ' + col)
    diffBetweenShowAndNoShowMeans.append(colDf.Showed.mean() - colDf2.Showed.mean())
    print('')

    y = (df.groupby(col).Showed.mean())
    if col != 'Handcap':
        x = ['Without '+ col, 'With '+col]
    plt.bar(x, y);
    plt.title('Rate of going to doctor by: '+ col)
    plt.ylabel('Rate')
    plt.show()

In the above graph, we managed to get a good idea of the likelihood of showing up at the appointment by age. It seems to be pretty uniform all the way up to much older ages. This makes sense - you don't get to 100 without having concern for your health. Except maybe for those individuals at 115. They seem very confident in their health.

With this, we have a potential list of factors that determine one's likeliness of going to their appointment:

'Scholarship', 'Hipertension', 'Diabetes', 'Handcap', 'SMS_received'.¶

Hipertension and Diabetes being the greatest marker towards going, and SMS_received being the greatest marker towards not going

Conclusions¶

Overall, from the data that we have had the chance to work with, we notice a few things that stand out:

In regards to Question 1, whether the Don't Have/Have columns make an impact:

  1. Having Hipertension, Diabetes, and Handcap 1 correlated with increase likelihood of showing over those without those conditions. This makes sense, since these tend to be chronic issues that need to be consistently cared for.
  2. Having a Scholarship or receiving and SMS correlated with a lower likelihood of showing to appointments. This was a bit more surprising as one would think those with a Scholarship or those who receive a reminder would be more likely to show. A few possible reasons could be conditions given by the scholarship fund or the fact that sms reminders are more likely to happen when there is a longer waiting time between making the appointment and going to the appointment. Both of these could be further subjects of study to get a more complete picture of the factors involved in going or not going.
  3. Having Alcoholism, however, seemed to have almost no correlation to whether or not one went to their appointment, as it was barely a 0.05% increase in likelihood of going, so it doesn't seem like something that should be studied in detail.
  4. The highest correlation with going to the appointment comes from having Hipertension, which has a 4% increase in likelihood of going. The factor with the largest negative correlation (and the largest overall correlation) came from whether they received an SMS or not at -10%, making this a prime factor to study and learn more about.

In regards to Question 2, whether Gender or Neighbourhood make an impact:

  1. The gender of the patient seemed to have almost no correlation to whether or not they went to their appointment, as there was barely a 0.35% difference in their rate of showing.
  2. However, there was a large difference in the number of those who made appointments by Gender, with women making 65% of the patients, almost double that of the men. While gender does not have a strong correlation on whether or not one goes to their appointment in this dataset, this could be a subject of further study on the issue of who seeks out and ends up receiving medical treatment in the country of Brazil.
  3. In regards to neighbourhoods - while they all are close in range of percentage showing (with approximately 50 of the 81 neighbourhoods in the 75%-85% range), there are a number of neighbourhoods that are distinctly above the average and below the average, inviting further study on whether that is simply a correlation or if there are other external factors within the neighbourhoods that increase or decrease the likelihood of going to one's appointment.
  4. The percentage of those who showed by appointment day is similarly uniformly distributed, more study could be done on which day of the week is likely to have more people show, if there is anything related to Holiday's that make people more or less likely to go, and to see if an increase or decrease in showing can be linked to an external campaign or event happening in the city, health related or otherwise.

Finally, there are some limitation to keep in mind and areas of further study:

  1. It is important to keep in mind that this data set is only over the course of 2 months, with not every day being filled.
  2. We don't as of yet know if this is a representative sample data for all the medical appointments over those two months or if it was curated to those dates that we were given or from a specific medical center. Going further we would want to know this information as it would inform how significant our findings from the data are.
  3. Another exciting subject of study with the more complete information would be to see waiting times over a larger period and if they are linked with lower likelihoods of going to appointment. Learning more about the reasons someone wanted to make an appointment, as well as what times the appointments were for, would be a beneficial aid in forming a model on what factors cause people to show or not show to their appointments.
